snippet.textDisplay: fun science fact: salt increases the boiling point of the water but that is obviously not the reason why the noodles boil quicker (since you would expect that it would take longer to boil if the boiling point is higher) : it is because, by the addition of salt, the heat storage capacity of the water increases, making the water boil faster. The amounts you use in cooking won't make that much of a difference though: iirc, 30 grams of salt increase the temperature by 1-3 degrees...

snippet.textDisplay:
"The usual boiling point of water is 100 °C or 212 °F at 1 atmosphere of pressure (at sea level). You would have to add 58 grams of salt just to raise the boiling point of a liter of water by one half of a degree Celsius. Basically, the amount of salt people add to water for cooking doesn't affect the boiling point at all."

Helmenstine, Anne Marie, Ph.D. "Does Adding Salt Lower the Boiling Point of Water?" ThoughtCo, Feb. 11, 2020, thoughtco.com/adding-salt-lower-boiling-point-water-607363.

https://www.thoughtco.com/adding-salt-lower-boiling-point-water-607363

snippet.textDisplay:
It kills me when the "level 4" scientist fails basic chemistry. Listen, you're never adding enough sodium to change the cooking time or temp. You add sodium to the water so the noodles change flavor. That only. Everything else is a wives tale. Adding enough salt to tangibly change the boiling point or cooking time is measured in cups, You're not going to add several cups of salt to a pot of water that you're going to eat.

I'm not a level 4. I'm a level 2 or less. Lets kill this myth. Lets mock "cooks" who push it.
